# Constructor ownership

If a collaborator or dependency does not change between method calls, it belongs
in the constructor — not created or accepted as a parameter in individual methods.

This applies to service objects, registries, parsers, repositories, and any
collaborator whose identity is fixed for the lifetime of the owning object.

```ruby
# BAD: collaborators created in method body
class DependencyService
  def resolve(declarations, repositories)
    resolver = Resolver.new
    lockfile = Lockfile.new(@dir)
    resolved = resolver.resolve(declarations, repositories:)
    lockfile.lock(resolved)
  end
end

# GOOD: collaborators owned by the constructor
class DependencyService
  def initialize(resolver:, lockfile:)
    @resolver = resolver
    @lockfile = lockfile
  end

  def resolve(declarations)
    resolved = @resolver.resolve(declarations)
    @lockfile.lock(resolved)
  end
end
```

**Test for it:** if a value is passed to or created in a method but never varies
across calls, move it to the constructor. Method parameters are for values that
change per call (e.g., the declarations being resolved).
